# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tailwind-css
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is designed to enable the separation of content and presentation, including layout, colors, and fonts.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Separation of formatting and content also makes it feasible to present the same markup page in different styles for different rendering methods, such as on-screen, in print, by voice (via speech-based browser or screen reader), and on Braille-based tactile devices.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also has rules for alternative formatting if the content is accessed on a mobile device.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] The name *cascading* comes from the specified priority scheme to determine which declaration applies if more than one declaration of a property match a particular element.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] This cascading priority scheme is predictable.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] The CSS specifications are maintained by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Internet media type (MIME type) `text/css` is registered for use with CSS by RFC 2318 (March 1998).
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C operates a free CSS validation service for CSS documents.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] In addition to HTML, other markup languages support the use of CSS including XHTML, plain XML, SVG, and XUL.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is also used in the GTK widget toolkit.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] CSS has a simple syntax and uses a number of English keywords to specify the names of various style properties.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] A style sheet consists of a list of *rules*.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Each rule or rule-set consists of one or more *selectors*, and a *declaration block*.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] In CSS, *selectors* declare which part of the markup a style applies to by matching tags and attributes in the markup itself.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Classes and IDs are case-sensitive, start with letters, and can include alphanumeric characters, hyphens, and underscores.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] A class may apply to any number of instances of any element.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] An ID may only be applied to a single element.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] One example of a widely used pseudo-class is `:hover`, which identifies content only when the user "points to" the visible element, usually by holding the mouse cursor over it.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] It is appended to a selector as in `a:hover` or `#elementid:hover`.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] A pseudo-class classifies document elements, such as `:link` or `:visited`, whereas a *pseudo-element* makes a selection that may consist of partial elements, such as `::first-line` or `::first-letter`.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Note the distinction between the double-colon notation used for pseudo-elements and the single-colon notation used for pseudo-classes.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Multiple simple selectors may be joined using combinators to specify elements by location, element type, id, class, or any combination thereof.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] The order of the selectors is important.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] For example, `div .myClass {color: red;}` applies to all elements of class myClass that are inside div elements, whereas `.myClass div {color: red;}` applies to all div elements that are inside elements of class myClass.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] This is not to be confused with concatenated identifiers such as `div.myClass {color: red;}` which applies to div elements of class myClass.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] The following table provides a summary of selector syntax indicating usage and the version of CSS that introduced it.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] A declaration block consists of a pair of braces (`{}`) enclosing a semicolon-separated list of *declarations*.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Each declaration itself consists of a *property*, a colon (`:`), and a *value*.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Optional white-space may be around the declaration block, declarations, colons, and semi-colons for readability.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Properties are specified in the CSS standard.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Each property has a set of possible values.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Some properties can affect any type of element, and others apply only to particular groups of elements.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Values may be keywords, such as "center" or "inherit", or numerical values, such as `200px` (200 pixels), `50vw` (50 percent of the viewport width) or 80% (80 percent of the parent element's width).
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Color values can be specified with keywords (e.g.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] `rgb(255, 0, 0)`), RGBA values that specify both color and alpha transparency (e.g.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Non-zero numeric values representing linear measures must include a length unit, which is either an alphabetic code or abbreviation, as in `200px` or `50vw`; or a percentage sign, as in `80%`.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] These eight units were a feature of CSS 1 and retained in all subsequent revisions.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] The proposed CSS Values and Units Module Level 3 will, if adopted as a W3C Recommendation, provide seven further length units: `ch`; `Q`; `rem`; `vh`; `vmax`; `vmin`; and `vw`.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, nearly all presentational attributes of HTML documents were contained within the HTML markup.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] That is, all font colors, background styles, element alignments, borders, and sizes had to be explicitly described (often repeatedly) within the HTML.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] CSS lets authors move much of that information to another file, the style sheet, resulting in considerably simpler HTML.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] And additionally, as more and more devices are able to access responsive web pages, different screen sizes and layouts begin to appear.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Customizing a website for each device size is costly and increasingly difficult.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] The modular nature of CSS means that styles can be reused in different parts of a site or even across sites, promoting consistency and efficiency.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] For example, headings (`h1` elements), sub-headings (`h2`), sub-sub-headings (`h3`), etc., are defined structurally using HTML.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] In print and on the screen, choice of font, size, color and emphasis for these elements is *presentational*.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, document authors who wanted to assign such typographic characteristics to, say, all `h2` headings had to repeat HTML presentational markup for each occurrence of that heading type.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] This made documents more complex, larger, and more error-prone and difficult to maintain.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] CSS allows the separation of presentation from structure.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] CSS can define color, font, text alignment, size, borders, spacing, layout and many other typographic characteristics, and can do so independently for on-screen and printed views.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also defines non-visual styles, such as reading speed and emphasis for aural text readers.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C has now deprecated the use of all presentational HTML markup.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] The advantages of this may not be immediately clear but the power of CSS becomes more apparent when the style properties are placed in an internal style element or, even better, an external CSS file.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] All `h1` elements in the document will then automatically become red without requiring any explicit code.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] rather than by laboriously going through the document and changing the color for each individual `h1` element.
[src:tailwind-css/cascading-style-sheets] This further decouples the styling from the HTML document and makes it possible to restyle multiple documents by simply editing a shared external CSS file.
[src:tailwind-css/css-framework] A **CSS framework** is a software library allowing for easier, more standards-compliant web design using Cascading Style Sheets.
[src:tailwind-css/css-framework] Most of these frameworks contain at least a grid.
[src:tailwind-css/css-framework] More functional frameworks also come with more features and additional JavaScript based functions, but are mostly design oriented and focused around interactive UI patterns.
[src:tailwind-css/css-framework] This detail differentiates CSS frameworks from other JavaScript frameworks.
[src:tailwind-css/css-framework] Two notable and widely used examples are Bootstrap and Foundation.
[src:tailwind-css/css-framework] Bigger frameworks use a CSS interpreter such as Less or Sass.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] The **CSS grid layout** module excels at dividing a page into major regions or defining the relationship in terms of size, position, and layering between parts of a control built from HTML primitives.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] Like tables, grid layout enables an author to align elements into columns and rows.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] However, many more layouts are either possible or easier with CSS grid than they were with tables.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] For example, a grid container's child elements could position themselves so they actually overlap and layer, similar to CSS positioned elements.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] The example shows a three-column track grid with new rows created at a minimum of 100 pixels and a maximum of auto.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] Items have been placed onto the grid using line-based placement.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] This sample animation uses `display`, `grid-template-columns`, `grid-template-rows`, and `gap` to create the grid, and `grid-column` and `grid-row` to position items within in the grid.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] To view and edit the HTML and CSS used, click the 'Play' at the top right of the example.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] An overview of the various features provided in the CSS grid layout module.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] How grid layout fits together with other CSS features including flexbox, absolutely positioned elements, and `display: contents`.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] Grid lines and how to position items against those lines, including the `grid-area` properties, negative line numbers, spanning multiple cells, and creating grid gutters.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] Placing grid items using named template areas.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] Combining names and track sizes; placing grid items by defining named grid lined and template areas.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] How grid positions items that don't have any placement properties declared.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] Aligning, justifying, and centering grid items along the two axes of a grid layout.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] A look at the interaction between CSS grid layout, box alignment and writing modes, along with CSS logical and physical properties and values.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] A look at how CSS grid layout can both help and harm accessibility.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] A few different layouts demonstrating different techniques you can use when designing with CSS grid layouts, including using `grid-template-areas`, a 12-column flexible grid system, and a product listing using auto-placement.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] What subgrid does with use cases and design patterns that subgrid solves.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] Details what masonry layout is and it is used.
[src:tailwind-css/css-grid-layout] How box alignment works in the context of grid layout.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Use this **CSS reference** to browse an alphabetical index of all of the standard CSS properties, pseudo-classes, pseudo-elements, data types, functional notations and at-rules.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] You can also browse key CSS concepts and a list of selectors organized by type.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Also included is a brief DOM-CSS / CSSOM reference.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] See the index of *selectors*, *pseudo-classes*, and *pseudo-elements* below.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] The syntax for each specified *value* depends on the data type defined for each specified *property*.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] For a beginner-level introduction to the syntax of selectors, see our guide on CSS Selectors.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Be aware that any syntax error in a rule definition invalidates the entire rule.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Invalid rules are ignored by the browser.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Note that CSS rule definitions are entirely (Unicode) text-based, whereas DOM-CSS / CSSOM (the rule management system) is object-based.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] As the structure of at-rules varies widely, please see At-rule to find the syntax of the specific one you want.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] The following are the various selectors, which allow styles to be conditional based on various features of elements within the DOM.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Specifies that both `A` and `B` elements are selected.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] This is a grouping method to select several matching elements.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Combinators are selectors that establish a relationship between two or more simple selectors, such as "`A` is a child of `B`" or "`A` is adjacent to `B`", creating a complex selector.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Specifies that the elements selected by both `A` and `B` have the same parent and that the element selected by `B` immediately follows the element selected by `A` horizontally.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Specifies that the elements selected by both `A` and `B` share the same parent and that the element selected by `A` comes before—but not necessarily immediately before—the element selected by `B`.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Specifies that the element selected by `B` is the direct child of the element selected by `A`.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Specifies that the element selected by `B` is a descendant of the element selected by `A`, but is not necessarily a direct child.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Specifies that the element selected by `B` is located within the table column specified by `A`.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Elements which span multiple columns are considered to be a member of all of those columns.
[src:tailwind-css/css-reference] Specifies a special state of the selected element(s).
